    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "just happens to be a prayer by the Church for the Rapture (cf. 2:8 and comments). Now whatever confusion we may have run into in the rest of the chapter, Song of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` ends on a clear note. The book ends where both Testaments end\u2014with a reference to the Second Coming of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. The difference between the two Testaments, in this regard, is that the Old Testament ends with a warning to the Jews to get ready for the Second Advent of their Messiah (Mal. 4:4\u20136), while the New Testament ends with the Church praying for the return of her Saviour at the Rapture (Rev. 22:20). Song of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` ends where the New Testament ends. Look at\nverse 14: \u201cMake HASTE, my beloved.\u201d John `[char_John_Ref]` writes: \u201cHe which testifieth these things saith, Surely I come QUICKLY. Amen.\u201d \u201c Be thou like to a roe or to a young hart upon the mountains of spices.\u201d And we have run into this before back in 2:17. \u201c Until the day break, and the shadows flee away, turn, my beloved, and be thou like a roe or a young hart upon the mountains of Bether.\u201d The \u201cday break\u201d places the verse squarely at the Second Coming (see 2 Pet. 2:19). So although there may be many things in the Song of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` that no one, as yet, has the answer to, one thing is clear. The love of a Christian for his Lord should always culminate in a \u201clove\u201d for \u201chis appearing\u201d (2 Tim 4:8; 1 Pet 1:7\u20138). There should be no hope dearer to a believer than the \u201cblessed hope\u201d (Tit. 2:13). And the prayer of a Christian should never be \u201cwait a little longer, please, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`,\u201d but \u201churry up a little quicker, please, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u201d! \u201c Even so, come, Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`.\u201d Song Of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` Commentary THE DOCTRINE OF THE GREAT DEEPS ( HEB. 8-9) Song Of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` Commentary Song Of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` Commentary Other works available on Kindle Entire publication list at www.kjv1611.org Cover @page {padding: 0pt; margin:0pt} body { text-align: center; padding:0pt; margin: 0pt; } THE BOOK OF SONG OF SOLOMON Dr. Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` S. Ruckman President, Pensacola Bible Institute B.A., B.D., M.A., Th.M., Ph.D. COPYRIGHT \u00a9 2010 by Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` S. Ruckman All Rights Reserved (PRINT) ISBN 1-58026-022-5 PUBLISHER\u2019S NOTE The Scripture quotations found herein are from the text of the Authorized King James Version of the Bible. Any deviations therefrom are not intentional. BB BOOKSTORE P.O. Box 7135 Pensacola, FL 32534 www.kjv1611.org Other works available on Kindle TABLE OF CONTENTS Introduction\nverse 14 just happens to be a prayer by the Church for the Rapture (cf. 2:8 and comments). Now whatever confusion we may have run into in the rest of the chapter, Song of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` ends on a clear note. The book ends where both Testaments end\u2014with a reference to the Second Coming of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. The difference between the two Testaments, in this regard, is that the Old Testament ends with a warning to the Jews to get ready for the Second Advent of their Messiah (Mal. 4:4\u20136), while the New Testament ends with the Church praying for the return of her Saviour at the Rapture (Rev. 22:20). Song of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` ends where the New Testament ends. Look at\nverse 14: \u201cMake HASTE, my beloved.\u201d John `[char_John_Ref]` writes: \u201cHe which testifieth these things saith, Surely I come QUICKLY. Amen.\u201d \u201cBe thou like to a roe or to a young hart upon the mountains of spices.\u201d And we have run into this before back in 2:17. \u201cUntil the day break, and the shadows flee away, turn, my beloved, and be thou like a roe or a young hart upon the mountains of Bether.\u201d The \u201cday break\u201d places the verse squarely at the [v_2Pe_2_19] Second Coming (see 2 Pet. 2:19). So although there may be many things in the Song of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` that no one, as yet, has the answer to, one thing is clear. The love of a Christian for his Lord should always culminate in a \u201clove\u201d for \u201chis appearing\u201d (2 Tim [v_1Pe_1_7] 4:8; 1 Pet 1:7\u20138). There should be no hope dearer to a [v_Tit_2_13] believer than the \u201cblessed hope\u201d (Tit. 2:13). And the prayer of a Christian should never be \u201cwait a little longer, please, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`,\u201d but \u201churry up a little quicker, please, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u201d! \u201cEven so, come, Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`.\u201d THE DOCTRINE OF THE GREAT DEEPS (HEB. 8-9) Other works available on Kindle Entire publication list at www.kjv1611.org",
